":"1284","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Danmark":"Denmark","Norringtoft, Thisted, Denmark":"Thisted, Denmark","Nordentoft Thisted Danmark":"Thisted, Denmark","Nordentoft, Tilsted, Thisted, Denmark":"Tilsted, Thisted, Denmark","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bild","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Erna, Inge, Irmgard, Johann, Udo, Volker.","German: from a short form of   Hildebrand   or other compound names with the same initial element, <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Hild</i> (of which <i>Hilda</i> is the Latin form), a short form of a compound name with the first element <i>Hild-</i>, e.g. ancient Germanic <i>Hildigard</i> or Old English <i>Hildgȳth</i>, from <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’. Compare   Hilliard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hildebrand","meanings":["German, Swedish, and English: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Hildebrand</i> (Old Norse <i>Hildibrandr</i>), composed of the elements <i>hild</i> ‘battle’ + <i>brand</i> ‘sword, firebrand’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine)."]},{"name":"Hilson","meanings":["English and Scottish:","patronymic meaning ‘son of <i>Hild</i>’; see   Hild   2.","patronymic meaning ‘son of <i>Hille</i>’; see   Hill   2."]},{"name":"Hilden","meanings":["German: patronymic from   Hild  .","German: habitational name from a place so called near Benrath.","English: habitational name from Hildenborough (Kent), from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>denn</i> ‘pasture’."]},{"name":"Hiltz","meanings":["Americanized form of South German <b>Hilz</b>, a variant of   Hild   1."]},{"name":"Hilde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Arlys, Erik, Iver, Juel, Selmer.","German: variant of   Hild   1.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Hilde, found in two places; the first element is most likely related to Old Norse <i>hjallr</i> ‘terrace, ledge’, the second one is from <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’."]},{"name":"Hildman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Eberhard, Otto.","Americanized form of German <b>Hildmann</b>: elaborated form of the personal name   Hild  ."]}]},{"name":"Strange","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): nickname for a newcomer to a district, from Middle English <i>strange</i> ‘foreign’ (Old French <i>estrange</i>, Latin <i>extraneus</i>, from <i>extra</i> ‘outside’).","Irish (Antrim): this name is also common in Ireland, where, in addition to its English etymology, it may represent an Anglicized form of any of several Irish names containing the element <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’, e.g.   Doyle  ,   Gallagher  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stranger","meanings":["English: nickname for a newcomer to an area, from Middle English <i>stra(u)nger(e)</i> ‘stranger, foreigner’ (Old French <i>estrangier</i>). Compare   Strange  ."]},{"name":"Doyle","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the Irish surname, Anglicized form of <i>Ó Dubhghaill</i> ‘descendant of <i>Dubhghall</i>’, from <i>dubh</i> ‘black’, ‘dark’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’ (  compare  Dougal   ). This was used as a byname for Scandinavians, in particular to distinguish the darker‐haired Danes from fair‐haired Norwegians."]},{"name":"Lestrange","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Strange   1 with fused Old French definite article <i>le</i>.","Irish: in Ireland, adopted for <b>Mac Conchoigchríche</b> ‘son of <i>Cúchoigcriche</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the borderland’. <i>Lestrange</i> was adopted for <b>Mac Conchoigchríche</b> probably due to the presence of a prominent family of Lestrange, of similar meaning, who settled in the counties of Westmeath and Offaly in the 16th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Strange Esgesen Bild was born in 1254. He had at least 2 sons with Ellen H